  "prompt": "Does the U.S. govt. have a contingency plan in case nobody decides to run for president? Or to vote for that matter?",
  "response": "The U.S. government has several provisions to address potential scenarios involving presidential elections:\n\n1. If no candidates run or no one receives a majority of electoral votes:\n- The House of Representatives would choose the president from among the top three candidates\n- Each state delegation gets one vote\n- A majority of state delegations is required to elect a president\n\n2. If there are no eligible candidates:\n- The Presidential Succession Act determines the line of succession\n- First, the Vice President would take over\n- If no Vice President is available, the line continues through:\n  - Speaker of the House\n  - President Pro Tempore of the Senate\n  - Cabinet members (in a specific order)\n\n3. Regarding voting:\n- There's no legal requirement for citizens to vote\n- Elections would proceed even with low voter turnout\n- States have laws and procedures to ensure elections can be held\n\nWhile these scenarios are highly unlikely, the Constitution and subsequent laws provide mechanisms to maintain governmental continuity and ensure leadership is determined even in extreme circumstances.\n\nUltimately, the system is designed with multiple safeguards to prevent a complete breakdown of the electoral process.",
